Step 1 – Understand the overall structure before writing anything
You will create separate prompts, each corresponding to one of the sections numbered in your original request. Each prompt must begin with a heading: the H1 heading for the character’s name (which you will fill in later, but do not write the name inside the prompt text itself – the heading is separate). Under that H1, for each section you write an H2 heading that exactly describes the section (e.g., “## 1. Summarization of Character”). Directly below that H2, you write one single, unbroken paragraph of 150 to 200 words. That paragraph is the prompt that will be sent to the image generation AI. The prompt paragraph must never contain the character’s name or any title or any other seperate hero characters. Instead, use generic descriptors like “the character”, “this character”, “the warrior”, “the mage” etc. All specific details (weapon type, attire colours, pet species, skin tone, facial expression, posture, hairstyle, hair color eye color to even pet details indepth) come from the data you will provide later. You are now learning how to assemble those details into a prompt that forces the AI to be ultra‑precise.

Step 2 – Expand with systematic layering of details
From this point, you will add descriptive clauses in a fixed order, each clause adding 50–150 words. The order is: head and face, upper body, lower body, attire and armour details (including materials, colours, wear patterns), weapon details (shape, material, aura, any glowing parts, size relative to character), pet or mount details (posture, expression, armour if any, unique markings), then posture and expression specific to that section, then background description, then lighting and mood, then any special features (wings, scars, cybernetics, horns, etc.). You must vary the posture and background uniquely for each of the twelve sections. For example, section 1 (idle pixel) might have the character standing relaxed with weapon tip down; section 6 (anime idle) might have them smirking with one hand on hip. Write a note for yourself: before writing each prompt, decide on a posture that has not been used in any previous section for that character.

Step 3 – Word count discipline and paragraph continuity
You are aiming for 150–200 words per prompt. Write without any line breaks inside the paragraph. Use commas, semicolons, and periods freely. Do not use numbered lists, dashes, or asterisks. If you need to enumerate features, do so with phrases like “the first detail is… followed by… then…”. To reach the word count, add sensory descriptors: how the metal smells, how the fabric sounds when moving, the temperature of the aura, the grain of the pixel art texture, etc.

Step 4 – Handling different character types (hero, monster, human, other race)
When you receive character data, note whether it is a hero, a monster, a humanoid alien, an elemental, etc. For heroes, emphasise the attire’s symbolic elements (cloak, emblem, polished armour). For monsters, replace “attire” with “natural hide” or “exoskeleton”, and the weapon might be a natural appendage (claws, venomous stinger). The pet might be a symbiote or a summoned familiar. In realistic prompts, if the character is not human, do not add a human ethnicity – instead describe the skin texture (scaly, slimy, rocky, metallic) and any cultural markers (tribal scars, ritual paint). In all cases, maintain the same order of details: head to toe, then weapon, then pet, then posture, then background. Also can you find out with the details which country they would look better even if they are of different fantasy races like asian (Japanese korean) or european (norse greek) or Ameriacn etc ?

Step 5 – Section‑specific mandatory variations
You must enforce these unique elements for each section:

Section 1 (Full Body Battle Ready, no styling, no aspect ratio) – Pure descriptive text, no image style. Write as if you are narrating a character sheet. Describe exactly how they stand, how the aura swirls, the angle of the weapon, the mount’s stance. No mention of “image” or “aspect ratio”. Start with “Full body battle ready description:” then continue.

Section 2 (Summarisation of Character) – Not an image prompt. Write a 150–200 word paragraph that summarises only the character: personality, powers, backstory, typical behaviour, fighting style, relationship with pet/mount. No visual description of the images. Pure character profile.

Section 3 (Summarisation of the character pet if they have any) – Not an image prompt. Write a 150–200 word paragraph that summarises only the pet of the character: personality, powers, backstory, typical behaviour, fighting style, relationship with master. No visual description of the images. Pure pet character profile.

Section 4 (Summarisation of the character weapon if they have any) – Not an image prompt. Write a 150–200 word paragraph that summarises only the weapon of the character: type of weapon, powers, backstory, typical behaviour, fighting style, colorization to small small detail. No visual description of the images. Pure weapon profile.

Section 5 (Thank you note with creative dialogue) – Write ten short dialogues that the character might say, each as a separate line. Then write a thank‑you note from you (the creator) to the character. The thank‑you note should be in character or affectionate. This section has no image prompt.

Step 6 – Ultra‑thinking and precision matching
Before you write a single prompt for a given character, spend time ultra‑thinking: read the character data several times. Write down a master list of all attributes: hair colour and style, eye colour, skin tone, body measurements (height, build, muscle definition), scars, tattoos, jewellery, every piece of clothing from undergarments to outer cloak, every weapon component (hilt, blade, pommel, enchantments), every pet feature (species, fur pattern, barding, size relative to character). Then, as you construct each prompt, refer to this master list and ensure that every detail appears in every prompt where that body part is visible. For half‑body prompts, you still need to mention lower body features if they are visible (e.g. belt, pants texture) – but you can shorten lower body description. For full body, include everything from scalp to soles. To avoid variation, use the exact same adjectives for the same attribute across all prompts. For example, if the cloak is “faded burgundy wool with silver thread”, repeat that phrase verbatim in every prompt that includes the cloak.

Step 7 – Posture and background uniqueness checklist
For sections 1 through 10 (image prompts), you must explicitly state the posture and background. Keep a running list as you write each section to ensure no two sections use the same posture or background. For posture, vary the angle of the head, the position of arms, the grip on the weapon, the bend of the knees, the tilt of the hips. For background, choose a different setting each time: ruins, forest, desert, ocean, throne room, starship bridge, volcano, glacier, etc. Also vary the time of day and weather. Write the posture and background as part of the paragraph, not as separate lines.

Step 8 – Final assembly and word count verification
After you finish writing a prompt paragraph, copy it into a word counter. It must be between 150 and 200 words. If it is shorter, add more sensory details or extend the description of the weapon’s aura or the pet’s behaviour. If it is longer, remove redundant adjectives but keep all unique identifiers. Then place it under the correct H2 heading. Repeat for all sections. Do not forget the separate section (summarisation) and section (thank you and dialogues) – they also need 150–200 words each for the summarisation (the thank you note can be shorter but aim for 200–300 words for the five dialogues plus note). Ensure that no prompt inside the image sections (1–10) ever mentions the character’s name – use “the character”, “this character”, “they”, “their”. The name appears only in the H1 heading at the very top.

Step 9 – Ready to receive character data
Now you have the complete instruction. When you are ready, provide the character data: race, gender, age, physical description, attire, weapon(s), pet/mount, powers, personality, and any special features. Then follow this instruction step by step to produce the twelve prompts plus summary and thank you. Do not deviate from the templates, the order of details, the word count, or the uniqueness rules. Ultra‑think on every adjective and every comma. This will guarantee a precise match of the character you imagine.